Name: a
Comment: anchor tag, creates a hyperlink

Name: abbr
Comment: defines an abbreviation or an acronym.  Use the global title attribute to show the description for the abbreviation/acronym when you mouse over the element.

Name: address
Comment: The <address> tag defines the contact information for the author/owner of a document or an article.

Name: area
Comment: defines an area inside an image map

Name: article
Comment: specifies independent, self-contained content. An article should make sense on its own, and it should be possible to distribute it independently of the rest of the site.

Name: aside
Comment: The <aside> tag defines some content aside from the content it is placed in. The <aside> content is often placed as a sidebar in a document.

Name: audio
Comment: used to embed sound content in a document

Name: b
Comment: makes the contained content bold.  Better to use css

Name: base
Comment: Specify a default URL and a default target for all links on a page

Name: bdi
Comment: BDI stands for Bi-Directional Isolation.  The <bdi> tag isolates a part of text that might be formatted in a different direction from other text outside it. This element is useful when embedding user-generated content with an unknown text direction.

Name: bdo
Comment: bi directional override

Name: blockquote
Comment: A section that is quoted from another source

Name: body
Comment: defines the document body.

Name: br
Comment: inserts a single line break

Name: button
Comment: defines a clickable button.

Name: canvas
Comment: used to draw graphics, on the fly, via scripting (usually JavaScript

Name: caption
Comment: used inside a table element, defines a table caption.  Must immediately follow the opening table tag

Name: cite
Comment: defines the title of a creative work

Name: code
Comment: Define some text as computer code

Name: col
Comment: specifies column properties for each column within a <colgroup> element.  useful for applying styles to entire columns, instead of repeating the styles for each cell, for each row

Name: colgroup
Comment: specifies a group of one or more columns in a table for formatting

Name: data
Comment: used to add a machine-readable translation of a given content

Name: datalist
Comment: specifies a list of pre-defined options for an <input> element

Name: dd
Comment: used to describe a term/name in a description list (see dl and dt)

Name: embed
Comment: defines text that has been deleted from a document. Browsers will usually strike a line through deleted text.

Name: details
Comment: creates a widget that can open/close to provide a summary or detailed set of information

Name: dfn
Comment: stands for the definition element and it specifies a term that is going to be defined within the content

Name: dialog
Comment: defines a dialog box or subwindow, making it easy to create popup dialogs and modals on a web page

Name: div
Comment: section in a document (the classic containing element

Name: dl
Comment: defines a description list

Name: dt
Comment: defines a term/name in a description list

Name: em
Comment: define emphasized text. The content inside is typically displayed in italic

Name: del
Comment: defines a container for an external resource, such as a web page, a picture, a media player

Name: fieldset
Comment: used to group related elements in a form

Name: figcaption
Comment: defines a caption for a <figure> element

Name: figure
Comment: specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc

Name: form
Comment: used to create an HTML form for user input

Name: h1
Comment: heading levels

Name: head
Comment: a container for metadata (data about data and is placed between the <html> tag and the <body> tag

Name: header
Comment: represents a container for introductory content or a set of navigational links.

Name: hgroup
Comment:
used to surround a heading and one or more

elements.

Name: hr
Comment: defines a thematic break in an HTML page (e.g. a shift of topic. Most often displayed as a horizontal rule that is used to separate content

Name: html
Comment: represents the root of an HTML document

Name: i
Comment: defines a part of text in an alternate voice or mood. The content inside is typically displayed in italic

Name: iframe
Comment: specifies an inline frame

Name: img
Comment: used to embed an image in an HTML page

Name: input
Comment: specifies an input field where the user can enter data

Name: ins
Comment: defines a text that has been inserted into a document. Browsers will usually underline inserted text

Name: kbd
Comment: used to define keyboard input. The content inside is displayed in the browser's default monospace font. This tag is not deprecated. However, it is possible to achieve richer effect by using CSS.

Name: label
Comment: defines a label for an element

Name: legend
Comment: defines a caption for the <fieldset> element

Name: li
Comment: defines a list item

Name: link
Comment: defines the relationship between the current document and an external resource

Name: main
Comment: Specify the main content of the document

Name: map
Comment: image map

Name: mark
Comment: defines text that should be marked or highlighted

Name: menu
Comment: defines an unordered list of content.  It is an alternative to the <ul> tag and browsers will treat these two lists equally.

Name: meta
Comment: describes metadata within an HTML document

Name: meter
Comment: defines a scalar measurement within a known range, or a fractional value. This is also known as a gauge

Name: nav
Comment: A set of navigation links

Name: noscript
Comment: defines an alternate content to be displayed to users that have disabled scripts in their browser

Name: object
Comment: defines a container for an external resource

Name: ol
Comment: defines an ordered list

Name: optgroup
Comment: used to group related options in a <select> element (drop-down list)

Name: option
Comment: defines an option in a select list

Name: output
Comment: used to represent the result of a calculation (like one performed by a script)

Name: p
Comment: defines a paragraph

Name: param
Comment: define parameters for an <object> element

Name: picture
Comment: gives web developers more flexibility in specifying image resources

Name: pre
Comment: defines preformatted text.  element is displayed in a fixed-width font, and the text preserves both spaces and line breaks. The text will be displayed exactly as written in the HTML source code.

Name: progress
Comment: Use the <progress> tag in conjunction with JavaScript to display the progress of a task.

Name: q
Comment: defines a short quotation

Name: rp
Comment: used to provide parentheses around a ruby text, to be shown by browsers that do not support ruby annotations

Name: rt
Comment: defines an explanation or pronunciation of characters (for East Asian typography in a ruby annotation

Name: ruby
Comment: specifies a ruby annotation. A ruby annotation is a small extra text, attached to the main text to indicate the pronunciation or meaning of the corresponding characters. This kind of annotation is often used in Japanese publications

Name: s
Comment: specifies text that is no longer correct, accurate or relevant. The text will be displayed with a line through it

Name: sample
Comment: define sample output from a computer program

Name: script
Comment: used to embed a client-side script (JavaScript)

Name: search
Comment: Elements inside a <search> element are typically form elements used to perform a search

Name: section
Comment: defines a section in a document

Name: select
Comment: creates a drop-down list

Name: small
Comment: defines smaller text (like copyright and other side-comments

Name: source
Comment: used to specify multiple media resources for media elements, such as <video>, <audio>, and <picture>

Name: span
Comment: an inline container used to mark up a part of a text; the inline version of div

Name: strong
Comment: used to define text with strong importance. The content inside is typically displayed in bold

Name: sub
Comment: defines subscript text. Subscript text appears half a character below the normal line, and is sometimes rendered in a smaller font

Name: summary
Comment: defines a visible heading for the <details> element. The heading can be clicked to view/hide the details. The <summary> element should be the first child element of the <details> element.

Name: sup
Comment: defines superscript text

Name: svg
Comment: defines a container for SVG graphics

Name: table
Comment: defines an HTML table

Name: tbody
Comment: used to group the body content in an HTML table

Name: td
Comment: defines a standard data cell in an HTML table (table detail)

Name: template
Comment: used as a container to hold some HTML content hidden from the user when the page loads. You can use the <template> tag if you have some HTML code you want to use over and over again, but not until you ask for it. To do this without the <template> tag, you have to create the HTML code with JavaScript to prevent the browser from rendering the code.

Name: textarea
Comment: defines a multi-line text input control

Name: tfoot
Comment: used to group footer content in an HTML table The <tfoot> element must have one or more <tr> tags inside

Name: th
Comment: defines a header cell in an HTML table

Name: thead
Comment: used to group header content in an HTML table must have one or more <tr> tags inside

Name: time
Comment: defines a specific time (or datetime)

Name: title
Comment: defines the title of the document

Name: tr
Comment: defines a row in an HTML table. contains one or more <th> or <td> elements

Name: track
Comment: specifies text tracks for <audio> or <video> elements

Name: u
Comment: represents some text that is unarticulated and styled differently from normal text, such as misspelled words

Name: ul
Comment: defines an unordered (bulleted list)

Name: var
Comment: used to defines a variable in programming or in a mathematical expression. This tag is not deprecated. However, it is possible to achieve richer effect by using CSS

Name: video
Comment: used to embed video content in a document

Name: wbr
Comment: (Word Break Opportunity tag specifies where in a text it would be ok to add a line-break. When a word is too long, the browser might break it at the wrong place. You can use the <wbr> element to add word break 	opportunities.
